    (insights
      "- Any human-AI collaboration sits on two independent axes: **judgment delegation** (who decides) and **loop tightness** (how often you exchange)
       - These axes are independent — you can delegate all decisions while maintaining tight loops, or retain full judgment with loose ones
       - Contextual factors (task risk, infrastructure quality, team expertise) determine where you *should* sit, not the model itself
       - You naturally oscillate: friction from inefficiency pushes toward delegation, friction from quality loss pulls back toward control
       - Bainbridge's irony applies directly: delegating execution erodes the skills you need to evaluate the output — the more it works, the less prepared you are when it doesn't"))

